    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nCurrent SSH config parser in `runtime/lua/vim/net/_ssh.lua` (#39378) relies on manual string manipulation and pattern matching. While this covers most common use cases, it is fragile when dealing with complex or non-standard ssh_config files.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nReplace manual patterns with a formal grammar (LPeg or Tree-sitter) to handle SSH config parsing, as discussed in #39378.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I feel like this is actually pretty easy with tree-sitter.\n\n```lua\nlocal host_pattern_query = vim.treesitter.query.parse(\"ssh_config\", [[\n  (host_declaration\n    argument: (pattern) @host_pattern)\n]])\n\n---Use tree-sitter to extract hostnames from an SSH config file\n---@param buf integer # Buffer number of the sshconfig file\nlocal function get_ssh_hosts(buf)\n  if vim.bo[buf].filetype ~= \"sshconfig\" then\n    error(\"unable to get ssh hosts from non-sshconfig file\")\n  end\n\n  local tree = assert(vim.treesitter.get_parser(buf)):parse()[1]\n\n  return vim.iter(vim.iter(host_pattern_query:iter_captures(tree:root(), buf)):totable())\n    :map(function(t)\n      local node = t[2]\n      local text = vim.treesitter.get_node_text(node, buf)\n      return vim.split(text, \",\")\n    end)\n    :flatten()\n    :filter(function(v)\n      -- Remove values containing *\n      return v:find(\"*\", nil, true) == nil\n    end)\n    :map(function(v)\n      -- Remove leading !\n      v = v:gsub(\"^!\", \"\")\n      return v\n    end)\n    :totable()\nend\n```\n\nConfiguration file:\n```sshconfig\nHost hello\n    HostName hello.example.com\n\nHost goodbye,bye\n    HostName goodbye.example.com\n\nHost nope,not.*,!yes,never\n    HostName idk.com\n    Port 1234\n```\nResult:\n```lua\n{ \"hello\", \"goodbye\", \"bye\", \"nope\", \"yes\", \"never\" }\n```\n\n(My one issue with it is the `vim.iter(vim.iter(...):totable())` thing, since `:flatten()` only works on list-iterators. Would love it if there was a better solution to that that I'm not aware of)",
            "created_at": "2026-05-18T22:45:47Z",
